    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_320048015" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/320048015" />
    <a title="Paquita Maria Sanchez" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2508169-paquita-maria-sanchez"><img alt="Paquita Maria Sanchez" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1594814608p2/2508169.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/320048015?book_show_action=true">Apr 27, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Paquita Maria Sanchez" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Paquita Maria Sanchez" href="/user/show/2508169-paquita-maria-sanchez">Paquita Maria Sanchez</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2508169-paquita-maria-sanchez?shelf=literature">literature</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer320048015" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15978489956707685538">Fick! What started out as the cause of me once again whining under my breath about Bernhard&apos;s head-clubbing repetition slowly evolved into a rewarding, mist upon the eyes causing, scrupulous bloodletting of Bernhard&apos;s personal guilt, nostalgia, and self-reflection resulting from the passing of his closest friend, literally Wittgenstein&apos;s nephew, Paul Wittgenstein. Paul was, as Bernhard and various Mental Health Professionals proclaimed, a certifiable Madman. However, Paul argued he was at least </span>
  <span id="freeText15978489956707685538" style="display:none">Fick! What started out as the cause of me once again whining under my breath about Bernhard's head-clubbing repetition slowly evolved into a rewarding, mist upon the eyes causing, scrupulous bloodletting of Bernhard's personal guilt, nostalgia, and self-reflection resulting from the passing of his closest friend, literally Wittgenstein's nephew, Paul Wittgenstein. Paul was, as Bernhard and various Mental Health Professionals proclaimed, a certifiable Madman. However, Paul argued he was at least less mad than his famous--yet posthumously disowned by the family--uncle Ludwig, "the maddest member of the family...to be a multimillionaire and a village schoolteacher is a bit perverse, don't you think?" <br /><br />Through examining their years-long friendship, Bernhard engages in ruminations on mortality, the nature of disease/deep disturbance and their effects on otherwise stable family, friend, and romantic relationships (and, thereby, the fleeting nature of all relationships <i>period</i>), Bernhard turns the scope inward and addresses his own failings as a human being and, by extension, as a friend. In a splattered chronology, Bernhard recalls brief moments of tenderness between himself and his, errr, 'eccentric?' friend coupled with bouts of extreme psychosis and deranged, occasionally illegal behavior on the latter's part. As Bernhard found himself retreating from his friend, he was forced to address a number of painful, oft-suppressed questions as to why he did so. As the novel unfolds, it digs deeper and deeper into the author's demons, these being collective demons. Sweet surface aside, Bernhard slowly flows out the truth of why he inevitably let Paul go, and in doing so, who He is and We are. To be brief, this is a therapy session on paper, but constructed with so much restraint from glamorizing or self-aggrandizing, in fact so intent on self-lacerating, that it becomes not only a moving, selfless memoir of a tragic friend met with a tragic destiny, but also a sage meditation on solipsism, artistic ego, philosophical shifts over a lifetime and the contradictions contained therein, and the generally fleeting nature of intimacy and companionship. Despite the previously mentioned repetition at the start of the novel (used as a means to draw comparisons between Bernhard's physical health problems and Paul's mental health problems in flashing neon 'Let me explain like you are a child' fashion), the novel is, on the whole, exquisitely composed. Some passages just slew me. <br /><br /><i>He was a restless character who always lived on his nerves and was perpetually out of control. He was a brooder, endlessly philosophizing and endlessly accusing. He was also an incredibly well trained observer, and over the years he developed his gift for observation to a fine art. He was the most ruthless observer and constantly found occasion to accuse. Nothing escaped his accusing tongue. Those who came under his scrutiny survived only a very short time before being savaged; once they had drawn </i>suspicion<i> upon themselves and become guilty of some </i>crime<i> or at least some </i>misdemeanor<i>, he would lambaste them them with the same words that I myself employ when I am roused to indignation, when I am forced to defend myself and take action against the insolence of the world in order to not to be put down and annihilated by it.</i><br /><br />Hey I know that guy! (Me!)<br /><br />For someone cast off out of combined selfishness and death-fear, Paul Wittgenstein clearly branded Bernhard's hard heart:<br /><br /><i>...before I met my friend there had been a period when I was prey to a morbid melancholy, if not depression, when I really believed I was lost, when for years I did no proper work but spent most of the day in a state of total apathy and often came close to putting an end to my life by my own hand. For years I had taken refuge in a terrible suicide brooding, which deadened my mind and made everything unendurable, above all myself--brooding on the utter futility all around me, into which I had been plunged by my general weakness, but above all my weakness of character. For a long time I could not imagine being </i>able<i> to go on living, or even existing. I was no longer capable of seizing upon any purpose in life that would have given me control over myself. Every morning upon waking I was inevitably caught up in this mechanism of suicide brooding, and I remained in this grip throughout the day. And I was deserted by everyone because </i>I<i> had deserted everyone--that is the truth--because I no longer wanted anyone...It was probably at the height of my despair--a word that I am not ashamed to use, as I no longer intend to deceive myself or gloss over in a society and a world that perpetually seeks to gloss over everything in a most sickening manner--that Paul appeared on the scene...</i><br /><br />Oooof. If that doesn't hit you in your soft, mushy parts, I don't know what to do for you. Have you ever had a friend or family member who was chronically sick and/or dying in one extreme or another, whether emotionally (through mental problems, drug/drink) or inescapably physically (disease, etc)? Do you have any guilt feelings associated with what is happening to or ended up happening to them? Do you wonder why you treat them as well or as poorly, why you hide from or embrace them during their times of distress? Read this. You won't like it, because it's really good.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15978489956707685538" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


