    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1461466292" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1461466292" />
    <a title="Dov Zeller" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/440651-dov-zeller"><img alt="Dov Zeller" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1478090196p2/440651.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1461466292?book_show_action=true">Dec 06, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dov Zeller" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dov Zeller" href="/user/show/440651-dov-zeller">Dov Zeller</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1461466292" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5419155531868957495">&quot;I am the happiest traveler—when I am on the move, moving on or moving off—but the unhappiest arriver.&quot; (88-89)<br/><br/>In &quot;Wittgenstein&apos;s Nephew&quot;, Bernhard explores his ideal place -- the place between places. It may be we never quite set out and never quite arrive in the pages of this book, but travel breathlessly, with few rests, as if life depends upon endless moving in much the way the roadrunner ought to keep moving and never look down. It&apos;s when we stop and take account that we realize how far the</span>
  <span id="freeText5419155531868957495" style="display:none">"I am the happiest traveler—when I am on the move, moving on or moving off—but the unhappiest arriver." (88-89)<br /><br />In "Wittgenstein's Nephew", Bernhard explores his ideal place -- the place between places. It may be we never quite set out and never quite arrive in the pages of this book, but travel breathlessly, with few rests, as if life depends upon endless moving in much the way the roadrunner ought to keep moving and never look down. It's when we stop and take account that we realize how far there is to fall.<br /><br />And yet, the whole book is a brave and at times scathing (and at times enthusiastically juvenile) introspection, which makes me wonder: must one be tethered to a place and a moment in order to perform this kind of text, or does introspection happen not in a profound ingoing stillness, as is sometimes imagined, but in movement between one reference and another, a desperate game of (tackle) connect the dots? <br /><br />Perhaps the answer is <i>both</i>, and the distinction between moving and standing still is itself called into question here. <br /><br />This book does have a home, and that home is the fictionalized and autobiographical connection between this fictionalized Bernhard and his friend Paul Wittgenstein, Ludwig Wittgenstein's nephew (and also the nephew of Dr. Salazar, just to throw us off a bit early in the novel.) Bernhard starts the novel/novella/memoir as he convalesces in the Steinhof hospital, which started off as "a psychiatric hospital and center for pulmonolgy." Bernhard is in the pulmonology department, Hermann Pavillon (apparently an anagrammatic reference to Bernhard's own name) and Paul W. is in the Ludwig Pavilion (referencing that other mad and genius Wittgenstein.) <br /><br />Bernhard and Paul W. start out in this hospital that both draws them together and alienates them from each other. They start and then they leave, but they never fully let go of their connection to illness nor to the hospital. In fact one of my favorite qualities of this novel is its interrogation of the relationship between a sick person's varying eras (times when they are more and less infirm), and between the sick person and their healthy communities. There is quite a soliloquy on the difficulty if not near-impossibility of genuine connection between the sick and the well. <br /><br />"And because a sick person is always deserted—to say anything else would be a gross lie—he must try to develop a quite superhuman energy if he wants to carry on from where he left off months before (or even years before, as I have had to do more than once.) A healthy person cannot understand this and immediately becomes impatient, and by his impatience he only makes life harder for the returning invalid, though he ought to be making it easier. The healthy have never had patience with the sick, nor, of course, have the sick ever had patience with the healthy. This fact must not be forgotten. For naturally the sick make far greater demands than the healthy, who, being healthy, have no need to make such demands. The sick do not understand the healthy and the healthy do not understand the sick..." <br /><br />Bernhard and Paul W. share a lot in the way of values and sensibilities, both because of their experience of illness, and their contentious relationship with Viennese culture and hstory. Bernhard finds a connection between the way Vienna treats its own "philosophizing" (something of a four letter word) children and the way the Wittgensteins as a family treat their "philosophizing" children (Paul and Ludvig. i.e., with contempt.) Bernhard feels victimized by Vienna just as he sees the two philosophical Wittgenstein's as victims of Vienna, and of their family as well. Vienna doesn't appreciate its artists and even when it offers honors, it is with condescension. (One of the funniest scenes in this book happens at a banquet in which Bernhard is to receive an award -- an activity he compares to being pissed on.)<br /><br />What else do Bernhard and PW share? Their love of cities, their hatred of the country, their delight in being between one place and another, game-ness to city-hop. Their love of music, their contempt for a lot of people, places and things; their pleasure in disrupting what they see as institutionalized smugness, arrogance or hypocrisy. <br /><br />It is always understood throughout their friendship that they are both to a degree frail, and one or the other will eventually return to the hospital, and may not leave again the next time. They are both headed toward the grand finale, and that grand finale will not be so grand, but rather, lonely and full of indignities much like life. <br /><br />As Paul becomes more frail, Bernhard finds himself withdrawing from the friendship, and he struggles deeply. He is angry with himself for pulling away from this intimacy. As he watches Paul fall apart from afar, he mourns but also delights in his memories of Paul. Neither of them were ever well. They were both chronically sick people. But they both have a wily and distinct liveliness, and both appreciate a certain horrific delectable comedy they see in every day life and can share (perhaps only?) with each other: <br /><br />"Gone were the days when he would give absurd accounts of his worldwide travels or when he would indulge his fondness for irony and sarcasm and deploy all his theatrical talents in merciless accounts of his family, whose contempt had hardened into hatred and whom he described as a curiosity cabinet containing a collection of Catholic-Jewish-Nazi specimens." (92)<br /><br />Gone were the days. But look how they live on, neither here nor there, but <i>here</i>. This book is elegiac though also it refuses a certain sentimentality. It's a short, strange, fascinating and worthwhile journey. I am still trying to piece together how the novel itself relates to this idea of in-between-ness.<br /><br />"All my forebears were afflicted by the same restlessness and could never bear to stay in one place for long. Three days in Vienna and I have had enough—three days in Nathal and I have had enough. In the last years of his life my friend adopted the same rhythm and often accompanied me to Nathal and back. Once in Nathal I asked myself what I am doing here, and I ask myself the same question when I arrive in Vienna. Basically, like nine tenths of humanity, I always want to be somewhere else, in the place I have just fled from. In recent years this condition has, if anything, become worse: I go to and from Vienna at diminishing intervals, and from Nathal I will open go to some other big city, to Venice or Rome and back, or to Prague and back. The truth is that I am happy only when I am sitting in the car, between the place I have just left and the place I am driving to. I am happy only when I am traveling; when I arrive, no matter where, I am suddenly the unhappiest person imaginable. Basically I am one of those people who cannot bear to be anywhere and are happy only between places. Years ago I believed that such a fatal condition would soon lead inevitably to total madness, which I have dreaded all my life, but in fact it preserved me from it. My friend Paul suffered from the same disease: for many years he was always traveling, simply in order to get away from one place and go to another, but he never succeeded in finding happiness on arrival..."<br /><br />I think this is one I will be coming back to. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="5419155531868957495" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


