<div id="review_338257783" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/338257783" />
    <a title="Steven" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4452312-steven"><img alt="Steven" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1449093910p2/4452312.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/338257783?book_show_action=true">Nov 29, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Steven" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Steven" href="/user/show/4452312-steven">Steven</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781400077564" href="/book/show/6327556-wittgenstein-s-nephew">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4452312-steven?shelf=literature">literature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4452312-steven?shelf=german">german</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4452312-steven?shelf=memoir">memoir</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4452312-steven?shelf=bernhard">bernhard</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4452312-steven?shelf=austrian">austrian</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer338257783" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4624267086389547054"><blockquote><i>&quot;The only difference between us is that Paul allowed himself to be utterly dominated by his madness, whereas I have never let myself be dominated by my equally serious madness; one might say that he was taken over by his madness, whereas I have always exploited mine.&quot;</i> (21)</blockquote><i>Wittgenstein&apos;s Nephew</i> begins in a Viennese hospital, where Thomas Bernhard and Paul Wittgenstein, nephew of the great philosopher Ludwig, are forced—for different but related reasons—to lie in separate wings. Bernhard is suffer</span>
  <span id="freeText4624267086389547054" style="display:none"><blockquote><i>"The only difference between us is that Paul allowed himself to be utterly dominated by his madness, whereas I have never let myself be dominated by my equally serious madness; one might say that he was taken over by his madness, whereas I have always exploited mine."</i> (21)</blockquote><i>Wittgenstein's Nephew</i> begins in a Viennese hospital, where Thomas Bernhard and Paul Wittgenstein, nephew of the great philosopher Ludwig, are forced—for different but related reasons—to lie in separate wings. Bernhard is suffering from a lung ailment, while Paul is suffering from madness. The story begins with and centers on illness, madness, and death, which are channeled by the setting of hospital. The story does eventually move beyond the clinic to a wider description of Paul's life and friendship with Bernhard, including among other things some reflections on music, Viennese society, and the Wittgenstein family. <br /><br />Although much of it is somber, especially the ending, there were some genuinely humorous moments (bitingly funny, as one would except from Bernhard). Especially the part about literary prizes was hilarious; I laughed at the following so hard, perhaps more than I should have, and more than once:<blockquote><i>"It then fell to me to say a few words, by way of thanks for the prize, as it were. Just before the ceremony, in great haste and with the greatest reluctance, I had jotted down a few sentences, amounting to a small philosophical digression, the upshot of which was that man was a wretched creature and death a certainty."</i> (71)</blockquote></span>
  <a data-text-id="4624267086389547054" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


