<div id="review_168114139" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/168114139" />
    <a title="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2190636-joselito-honestly-and-brilliantly"><img alt="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1349701607p2/2190636.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/168114139?book_show_action=true">May 14, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" href="/user/show/2190636-joselito-honestly-and-brilliantly">Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer168114139" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1747992646537237075">Had this not been part fiction I would have unhesitatingly called its author, Thomas Bernhard, insane. Or, at the very least, a difficult, incomprehensible eccentric. He writes here about his friend Paul Wittgenstein, a nephew of the philosopher Ludwig Wittgenstein whose philosophy of language I studied in college but never understood. To Thomas Bernhard both Ludwig and Paul were mad philosophers, the only difference between them being that Ludwig was published and became famous while Paul never</span>
  <span id="freeText1747992646537237075" style="display:none">Had this not been part fiction I would have unhesitatingly called its author, Thomas Bernhard, insane. Or, at the very least, a difficult, incomprehensible eccentric. He writes here about his friend Paul Wittgenstein, a nephew of the philosopher Ludwig Wittgenstein whose philosophy of language I studied in college but never understood. To Thomas Bernhard both Ludwig and Paul were mad philosophers, the only difference between them being that Ludwig was published and became famous while Paul never wrote anything and therefore died in obscurity. Paul, however, was Thomas Bernhard's friend. More than this, Paul was the only thing in this world whom he did not hate (well, except maybe another woman, an old one, most likely his mother but whom he refused to identify) and about whom he could say some nice things. Towards the end, nonetheless, when Paul had lost his vivacity and money which made him such a delightful companion before, he avoided him.<br /><br />A novel with just one paragraph (and don't tell me there was no need to break it down to two or more paragraphs--there were a lot of switch in topics where paragraphs were called for but it just went on and on). This begins in a Viennese hospital where, in separate pavilions, Paul and Thomas Bernhard are confined, both dying. Paul, of madness; Thomas, of a lung ailment. This is the gayest part of this masterpiece of glumness which is so morose that it brought me indescribable tears of joy when I finished reading it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1747992646537237075" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


