<div id="review_3653484495" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3653484495" />
    <a title="Paul" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30751659-paul"><img alt="Paul" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1525336320p2/30751659.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3653484495?book_show_action=true">Nov 23, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Paul" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Paul" href="/user/show/30751659-paul">Paul</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/19452715-wittgenstein-s-nephew">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3653484495" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1538339465372297288"><i>Wittgenstein&apos;s Nephew</i> doesn&apos;t deviate from Thomas Bernhard&apos;s established model - a single paragraph across 100 pages, ire and pathos, elitism and anti-elitism, relentless invective against Österreich&apos;s charming capital (and, in this case, against its beautiful coffee houses)... And, of course, it&apos;s none the worse for that. That solitary paragraph might seem off-putting to our modern attention spans but such is the energy of Bernhard&apos;s prose that this short novel is an easy read. <br/><br/><i>Wittgenstein&apos;s N</i></span>
  <span id="freeText1538339465372297288" style="display:none"><i>Wittgenstein's Nephew</i> doesn't deviate from Thomas Bernhard's established model - a single paragraph across 100 pages, ire and pathos, elitism and anti-elitism, relentless invective against Österreich's charming capital (and, in this case, against its beautiful coffee houses)... And, of course, it's none the worse for that. That solitary paragraph might seem off-putting to our modern attention spans but such is the energy of Bernhard's prose that this short novel is an easy read. <br /><br /><i>Wittgenstein's Nephew</i> is a novel about the author's friendship with Paul, the son of the philosopher's brother. Paul is immensely erudite but also a madman, incarcerated, at diminishing intervals, in various psychiatric institutions. The prompt for this action is generally the intimation that Paul is about to kill someone. In many ways, the philosopher's nephew is the mirror image of Bernhard. Both love to talk for hours about painting and 'serious' music, to bitch about mutual acquaintances, to inveigh against the perceived hypocrisy and insularity of Austrian society. No wonder they were such great friends but that their friendship was so fragile. The two men were two/too alike.<br /><br /><i>Wittgenstein's Nephew</i> is also the story of Paul Wittgenstein's mental disintegration. It is, by turns, uproariously funny and intensely moving. It is typical of Bernhard that one of his closest relationships should be with such a character. He met his lifelong 'companion' when he was 18. She was already 55. 'And why not?' one might ask, but it's hardly conventional. <br /><br />Bernhard is the most honest of writers. It becomes clear that what he hates in the Viennese artistic beau monde is what he loathes in himself. He steers clear of the literary coffee houses because they are full of people like himself. A man with such ferocious intelligence naturally has great self-knowledge. Towards the end of his great friend's life, Bernhard admits to avoiding Paul like everyone else because "We shun those who bear the mark of death". It's well known that Bernhard had his own physical and mental health problems. Of their friendship he writes:<br /><br /><i>It seems to me I was basically nothing but the twelve-year witness of his dying, who drew from his friend's dying much of the strength he needed for his own survival.</i><br /><br />"I am not a good person," he writes. Bernhard admits to us that he was out of the country when his friend died, didn't attend the funeral and hasn't visited his grave. Cowardly? Self-obsessed? That's what you get from this writer; intellectual and emotional honesty.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1538339465372297288" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


