<div id="review_2096204287" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2096204287" />
    <a title="Christopher Robinson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/62328457-christopher-robinson"><img alt="Christopher Robinson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1503277082p2/62328457.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2096204287?book_show_action=true">Dec 28, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Christopher Robinson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Christopher Robinson" href="/user/show/62328457-christopher-robinson">Christopher Robinson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781400077564" href="/book/show/6327556-wittgenstein-s-nephew">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/62328457-christopher-robinson?shelf=read-and-kept">read-and-kept</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/62328457-christopher-robinson?shelf=favorite-books">favorite-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/62328457-christopher-robinson?shelf=read-2020">read-2020</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2096204287" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12288584430115819967">“Sitting on the park bench, I suddenly saw it all clearly again, as I was not ashamed of the pathos I succumbed to, of the fine words that I allowed to flow into me for the very first time; they suddenly made me feel tremendously good, and I made no attempt to tone them down. I let them all descend on me like a refreshing rain. And today it seems to me that we can count on the fingers of one hand all the people who have really meant anything to us in the course of our lives, and very often this </span>
  <span id="freeText12288584430115819967" style="display:none">“Sitting on the park bench, I suddenly saw it all clearly again, as I was not ashamed of the pathos I succumbed to, of the fine words that I allowed to flow into me for the very first time; they suddenly made me feel tremendously good, and I made no attempt to tone them down. I let them all descend on me like a refreshing rain. And today it seems to me that we can count on the fingers of one hand all the people who have really meant anything to us in the course of our lives, and very often this one hand protests at our perversity in believing that we need a whole hand in order to count them, for to be honest we could probably make due without a single finger. There are times, however, when life is endurable, and at such times we occasionally manage to count three or four people to whom in the long run we owe something, and not just something but a great deal—people who have meant everything and been everything to us at certain critical moments or certain critical periods of our lives.” (p. 80 -81)<br /><br />Also, see pages 46 - 49 for some of the finest, most profound writing on the subject of chronic illness I’ve ever read anywhere.<br /><br />- - - - - - - - - - - -<br /><br />At turns hilarious and brutally sad, <i>Wittgenstein’s Nephew</i> find Bernhard in a (slightly) softer mode than usual. It is still loaded with his usual darkness, gallows humor, pessimism and obsessive repetition, but taken as a whole it is also quite a beautiful tribute to a deep and complicated friendship. It adds another fascinating layer of complexity to the story of one of the 20th century’s most singular and fascinating writers. <br /><br />Highly recommended, especially to fans of Bernhard’s fiction who want to learn more about the man himself. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12288584430115819967" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


