    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_35009474" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/35009474" />
    <a title="John" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/708858-john"><img alt="John" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1488290631p2/708858.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/35009474?book_show_action=true">Oct 10, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="John" class="user" itemprop="url" name="John" href="/user/show/708858-john">John</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">readers who like a laugh, a shock, a challenge</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to John by: </span>
      maybe Donald Barthelme
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/708858-john?shelf=novellas-edgy-magnificent">novellas-edgy-magnificent</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/708858-john?shelf=fine-strange-foreign">fine-strange-foreign</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer35009474" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4032815100135699542">Call it the contra-convalescent novel, in which laughter is the worst medicine &amp; yet we can&apos;t help sticking out our arms for a fresh shot, because anyway it hurts more to be up on your feet than laid out in a hospital. Or is this a novella? WITTGENSTEIN&apos;S NEPHEW has no chapter breaks, anyway, nor paragraph breaks either. As its shaggy-dog cynicism &amp; worldliness spools out, the work may even rise to the technical challenge of carving out a new late-20th-Century form. This thing of darkness, fasci</span>
  <span id="freeText4032815100135699542" style="display:none">Call it the contra-convalescent novel, in which laughter is the worst medicine &amp; yet we can't help sticking out our arms for a fresh shot, because anyway it hurts more to be up on your feet than laid out in a hospital. Or is this a novella? WITTGENSTEIN'S NEPHEW has no chapter breaks, anyway, nor paragraph breaks either. As its shaggy-dog cynicism &amp; worldliness spools out, the work may even rise to the technical challenge of carving out a new late-20th-Century form. This thing of darkness, fascinating &amp; booklined darkness, was wrought -- so claims its narrator, one Thomas Bernhard -- from his late-1960s stay in a Vienna pulmonary ward, when he shared a room with the nephew of the title. Fiercely antisocial &amp;/or certifiably mad, this nephew is heir to his forebear's blistering intelligence, the kind that can shear away any pretension with a brief sequence of refined polysyllables interpolated with a perfectly-placed gutter obscenity or two, &amp; he's heir as well to one of the greatest fortunes in central Europe, four or five generations' worth of hoarded cash, a vast sum he's made himself sick trying to get rid of. The narrative proceeds via this desperate &amp; diseased unburdening, undoing all sorts of pieties &amp; vanities, &amp; the impulse to strip away the glitter soon infects the narrator's spirit as well; his artistic calling, the impulse behind this very writing, comes to seem just another new suit of clothes for the Emperor. The "climax" (the term must go in quotes, here) seems to me the most uproarious &amp; withering assault on the business of giving &amp; receiving literary awards ever committed to print, &amp; and altogether too true. Bernhard is the true inheritor to Beckett, picking at scabs clear down to the bone, yet leaving us gap-jawed at the seeping humanity he reveals. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4032815100135699542" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


